  1. Based on my model, for a 1% increase in those living state with coastline, I would expect a 2.5% increase in percentage of a state population that agrees that climate change is happening. Task 2. UCSB Campus Climate Survey– Respectfulness by Respondent Race/Ethnicity

  1. I am looking at continuous data with more than two independent variables, so I am going to use a chi-squared test. This will answer the question: is there a significant association between perceived respect and racial groups on UCSB campus?

  2. There is a significant difference between racial groups and perceived levels of respect on UCSB campus.

Task 4. Pyraclostrobin residue on crops

  1. In my exploratory visualization of the data, first I made a scatterplot to see the values of the pesticide chemical measurements for each crop. Looking at these, there appears to be a difference between strawberries and carrots, with strawberries having more measurements that are much higher. I would initally expect to use a t-test to compare the values for significant differences; in order to test this, I created histograms and q-q plots for each crop. Both of the histograms look non-normal, with a low peak and a long tail up to higher values. The q-q plots also are more curved than linear. Even if the data looked non-normal, with a large enough sample size, I would still consider doing a t-test, but with a summary table, I see that the sample size for carrots is less than 30. Thus, I choose to do a Mann Whitney-U Test because it is a non-parametric method to compare ranks between a continuous measured output.

## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

  1. Pesticide use of Pyraclostrobin differed between the two crops, with a higher median pesticide measurement (0.022 ppm) for carrots (n = 15), versus a pesticide measurement median of 0.071 ppm for strawberries (n = 40). A Mann-Whitney U test revealed that the difference was significant (W = 508.5, p <0.001) with a large effect size (Cliff’s delta = 0.695).

Task 5. Pesticides by County, California

# top ten CA counties ranked by pounds applied per mile plot

county_pest_plot <- ca_county_pesticides %>% 
  clean_names() %>% #make all names snake case
  mutate(pest_per_mile=pounds_active_pesticide_ingredient_used/county_area_square_miles) %>%  # add a column for pounds pesticide per square mile area in county
  arrange(-.$pest_per_mile) %>% # arrange by pesticide per area
  head(10) %>% #keep the top ten counties by pesticide per area
  ggplot(.,aes(x=reorder(county,pest_per_mile), y=pest_per_mile)) + #create a plot of county and pesticide use per mile, ordered by pest per mile
  geom_col(fill="grey49") + # column graph w slightly lighter bars than default 
  coord_flip() +
   theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), 
      panel.background = element_blank(),
      axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"),
      text = element_text(family = "Times New Roman")) + #aesthetics
  labs(x = "County",
       y = "Pesticide Applied"~(lbs/mi^2)) + #labels for the axes-- coord flip switched these earlier, so xlab is for the y axis now
       theme(legend.position = "none") + #no legend 
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0,0))+ # move data to align w y axis
  ggtitle("Top 10 California Counties by Pesticide Use")

county_pest_plot
